Khepra-Lesh (the "Lost City") was a jurisdictional hinge-city where three legal systems overlapped: oasis water-law, pyramid funerary jurisdiction, and eastern desert caravan law.
Its founding charter established a balancing court to prevent oasis councils or pyramid priesthoods from monopolizing desert authority.

Public squares doubled as flow adjudication courts. Taxation used volumetric units. Police powers were tied to canal gates and ration tablets.

When the Twin Sovereigns split dynastic authority, Khepra-Lesh became one of the few places where both doctrines coexisted.
It produced "double rulings": the same case adjudicated under surface law and tomb law. The compromise created irreversible contradictions.

The city died during the Ninth Meridian fracture. Water schedules failed. Court authority split between solar and moon officers.
Cistern sabotage began. Final lockout decrees sealed the deep reliquary and criminalized former civic offices.
The city petrified into competing emergency regimes until both ran out of water, personnel, and legitimacy.

At the depth of the Tyrant Crypt Ring lies the Hollow Diadem, worn by the last adjudicator who fused office, judgment, and burial protocol into one permanent mandate.
